{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Per-token approvals are not cleared on owner or operator transfers, allowing stale approved addresses to steal NFTs","locations":["0x79a7d3559d73ea032120a69e59223d4375deb595/Contract.sol:311","0x79a7d3559d73ea032120a69e59223d4375deb595/Contract.sol:337","0x79a7d3559d73ea032120a69e59223d4375deb595/Contract.sol:354","0x79a7d3559d73ea032120a69e59223d4375deb595/Contract.sol:443"],"claim":"`approval[tokenId]` is only cleared in the branch where the approved address itself calls `transferFrom`/`safeTransferFrom`. When the owner or an `approvalAll` operator moves the NFT, `_transfer` updates balances and ownership but never resets the old single-token approval. That stale approved address remains authorized against the new owner and can later call `transferFrom` to seize the token. The same stale approval also survives a burn because `burn()` calls `_transfer` directly.","impact":"A previously approved address can steal NFTs after they are sold or otherwise transferred by the owner/operator. It can also reclaim a burned NFT from `DEAD_ADDRESS` without paying the 5 DAO restore cost, bypassing the intended restoration payment flow.","paths":["Owner approves attacker for token `id` via `approve(attacker, id)` -> owner or operator transfers token to a buyer via `transferFrom` or `safeTransferFrom` -> approval is not cleared -> attacker calls `transferFrom(buyer, attacker, id)` and succeeds.","Owner approves attacker for token `id` -> owner calls `burn(id)` -> token moves to `DEAD_ADDRESS` but approval persists -> attacker calls `transferFrom(DEAD_ADDRESS, attacker, id)` and restores the NFT without paying DAO fees."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"Low","confidence":"high","title":"ERC165 advertises enumerable and receiver interfaces that the contract does not actually honor","locations":["0x79a7d3559d73ea032120a69e59223d4375deb595/Contract.sol:232","0x79a7d3559d73ea032120a69e59223d4375deb595/Contract.sol:241","0x79a7d3559d73ea032120a69e59223d4375deb595/Contract.sol:253","0x79a7d3559d73ea032120a69e59223d4375deb595/Contract.sol:428","0x79a7d3559d73ea032120a69e59223d4375deb595/Contract.sol:451"],"claim":"`supportsInterface()` returns true for `IERC721Enumerable` and `IERC721TokenReceiver`, but the implementation does not satisfy either interface's expected behavior. `totalSupply()` returns `max` rather than the number of assigned tokens, `tokenOfOwnerByIndex()` ignores `_owner` and simply returns `_index` if any token is assigned there, and `onERC721Received()` always reverts instead of accepting transfers and returning the selector.","impact":"Integrators that trust ERC165 can mis-enumerate ownership, miscount supply, or attempt safe transfers into this contract and hit unexpected reverts. That can break marketplace indexing, custody flows, and other integrations built around standard ERC721 behavior.","paths":["Integrator checks `supportsInterface(type(IERC721Enumerable).interfaceId)` -> uses `totalSupply`/`tokenOfOwnerByIndex` to enumerate holdings -> receives token IDs unrelated to the queried owner or unminted IDs -> downstream accounting or UI logic misbehaves.","External contract or bridge checks `supportsInterface(type(IERC721TokenReceiver).interfaceId)` -> attempts `safeTransferFrom` into this contract -> `onERC721Received()` reverts and the transfer path fails unexpectedly."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Low","confidence":"high","title":"Approval events log the caller instead of the actual token owner","locations":["0x79a7d3559d73ea032120a69e59223d4375deb595/Contract.sol:320","0x79a7d3559d73ea032120a69e59223d4375deb595/Contract.sol:346","0x79a7d3559d73ea032120a69e59223d4375deb595/Contract.sol:363","0x79a7d3559d73ea032120a69e59223d4375deb595/Contract.sol:383"],"claim":"The contract emits `Approval(msg.sender, ...)` instead of `Approval(owner, ...)`. When an operator approves a spender, or when an approved spender clears approval during transfer, the log's indexed owner field does not match the token's true owner.","impact":"Off-chain systems that reconstruct approval state from logs can desynchronize from on-chain reality, causing incorrect approval displays, stale listings, or misattributed authorization history.","paths":["Owner grants `setApprovalForAll(operator, true)` -> operator calls `approve(spender, tokenId)` -> emitted `Approval` event records `operator` as owner even though `ownerOf(tokenId)` is unchanged.","Approved spender transfers the token -> contract emits approval-clear event with the spender in the owner field -> log-based indexers can mis-handle approval invalidation."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Incomplete require statement causes compilation failure","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Rejected. `require(_holder != address(0));` is valid Solidity syntax and compiles normally."},{"title":"Unchecked return values in restore function","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Rejected. Both ERC20 `transferFrom` calls in `restore()` are wrapped in `require`, so restoration cannot proceed if either payment fails."},{"title":"Missing token existence validation in burn function","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Rejected. `burn()` uses a mapping, not an array; out-of-range IDs do not read garbage. For unset IDs `ownership[id]` is `address(0)`, so the owner check fails for any real caller."},{"title":"Missing token existence validation in restore function","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Rejected. Mapping reads for unset IDs return `address(0)`, so `require(DEAD_ADDRESS == ownership[id])` fails. There is no out-of-bounds read primitive here."},{"title":"Missing zero-address validation in constructor","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Rejected. This is deployer misconfiguration risk, not a permissionless protocol vulnerability."},{"title":"Incorrect event parameter ordering in Transfer event","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Rejected. `emit Transfer(_from, _to, _tokenId)` uses the correct ERC721 argument order, and the candidate's duplicate-event rationale is not a vulnerability."},{"title":"Curator role is not immutable and can be renounced","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Rejected. The current source has no `renounceOwnership()` path in the audited contract, and curator reassignment is an intentional privileged admin action rather than a security flaw."},{"title":"Missing SafeMath for arithmetic operations","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Rejected. The contract uses Solidity `^0.8.11`, which has built-in checked arithmetic."},{"title":"Token ID range not validated in approve function","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Rejected. `approve()` already checks `_tokenId < max`, and non-minted tokens cannot be approved because the authorization check fails when `ownership[_tokenId]` is zero."},{"title":"Missing validation in tokenOfOwnerByIndex","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Merged into F-002. The function is indeed broken, but the reportable issue is the broader false `IERC721Enumerable` support claim and resulting integration breakage."},{"title":"onERC721Received reverts instead of returning selector","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Merged into F-002. Reverting is only reportable here because `supportsInterface()` advertises receiver support."},{"title":"Missing Return Values in ERC721 Interface Functions","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Rejected. The candidate misstates the code: `supportsInterface()` returns true for both `IERC721Enumerable` and `IERC721TokenReceiver`."}]}
